### Description

We have the need for getting visibility into initial Angular script load failures. This likely occurs because of our load balancer or our CDN serving bad assets. What is your recommended appproach for capturing these failures are reporting them to our logging? At the moment we are doing something like; 
```
<script>
	window.addEventListener('error', (event) => {
		if (isAngularLoaded()) {
			logError(event);
		}
	});

	function isAngularLoaded() {
		return !!document.querySelector('[ng-version]');
	}

	function logError(event) {
		// Send fetch request to our log server directly
	}
</script>
```
This is generic and captures much more than what we are looking for here. Ideally, we would be able to listen to Angular-critical scripts (like main.ts, vendor.ts, pollyfills.ts, ect).

### Proposed solution

Create documentation around page startup best practices including but not limited to initial script load failures,

### Alternatives considered

Leave it up the library consumers to figure out the best solution. We'd likely need to just query the DOM, find those ciritcal scripts (like main.ts, vendor.ts, pollyfills.ts, ect) and hook up error event listeners manually.
